rming > Aerobic > Bacillus > Non-motile, non-hemolytic", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Rods with squared-off ends; spore located centrally", "arrangement": "Chains/single rods", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Spore-forming (spores are non-motile in vivo — no flagella)", "Non-hemolytic on blood agar", "Large, white colonies on plain media"], "virulenceFactors": ["Anti-phagocytic capsule (poly-D-glutamic acid)", "Tripartite exotoxin (protective antigen, edema factor, lethal factor)"], "diseases": ["Cutaneous anthrax — contact with animal hides; painless black eschar (malignant pustule) with surrounding edema", "Pulmonary anthrax (Woolsorters' disease) — inhalation of spores from animal products (wool, hides); flu-like onset, rapid deterioration, can be fatal within 24 hours", "Gastrointestinal anthrax — ingestion of undercooked contaminated meat; nausea, vomiting, bloody diarrhea, can progress to shock"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-positive spore-forming rods, non-hemolytic, non-motile", "Large colonies on routine media"], "examPearls": ["Contact with animal hides/postal worker = classic exposure history", "Black eschar = pathognomonic cutaneous lesion", "Potential bioterrorism agent", "All 3 forms (cutaneous, pulmonary, GI) can disseminate to bacteremia and CNS infection, causing death"], "reservoir": "Soil; spores contaminate animal hides, wool, and can persist in environment for years", "transmission": "Cutaneous: contact with infected animal products through skin breaks. Pulmonary: inhalation of spores. GI: ingestion of undercooked contaminated meat.", "predisposingFactors": ["Occupational exposure: veterinarians, wool/hide workers, postal workers (historically, bioterrorism)"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Spores germinate at the site of entry. Cutaneous: raised red lesion forms within 2-5 days, vesiculates with dark fluid, then ruptures into a black eschar (malignant pustule) surrounded by ongoing edema/erythema. Pulmonary: spores inhaled into alveoli, germinate, toxin causes hemorrhagic mediastinitis; initial flu-like symptoms progress rapidly to respiratory failure. GI: ingested spores germinate in the gut, causing hemorrhagic enteritis.", "additionalNotes": "Prevention: vaccination of at-risk populations (veterinarians) and livestock; public health education; avoid using meat from animals suspected to have died of anthrax; isolate suspected sick animals.", "treatment": "Antibiotics; vaccination for at-risk groups and livestock as prevention."}, {"id": "b_cereus", "scientificName": "Bacillus cereus", "classificationPath": "Gram-Positive Rods > Spore-forming > Aerobic > Bacillus > Motile, fully hemolytic, Gamma-phage sensitive", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Rods, similar to B. anthracis", "arrangement": "Chains/single rods", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Motile (unlike B. anthracis)", "Complete (beta) hemolysis on sheep blood agar", "Sensitive to gamma phage", "Spore-forming"], "virulenceFactors": ["Heat-stable preformed enterotoxin (emetic type) — formed during sporulation, survives cooking", "Heat-labile enterotoxin (diarrheal type) — formed during late exponential growth in food"], "diseases": ["Rapid-onset emetic food poisoning (1-5 hr incubation) — nausea/vomiting, mimics S. aureus food poisoning", "Diarrheal food poisoning (8-16 hr incubation) — abdominal pain and diarrhea, mimics Clostridium perfringens food poisoning"], "labDiagnosis": ["Motile spore-forming gram-positive rod, fully hemolytic, gamma-phage sensitive (distinguishes from B. anthracis)"], "examPearls": ["Classic association: FRIED RICE (rice held at room temp or reheated)", "Two distinct food-poisoning syndromes mimic Staph (emetic, fast) and Clostridium perfringens (diarrheal, slower)", "Food kept warm (not hot) at buffets is a classic risk scenario"], "reservoir": "Soil; grains, vegetables, dairy products", "transmission": "Foodborne — fried rice (rice cooked, left at room temperature, then reheated) is the classic vehicle", "detailedPathogenesis": "Spores survive cooking; if food is then held at room temperature, spores germinate into vegetative cells that produce enterotoxin. Emetic type: preformed heat-stable toxin ingested directly causes rapid vomiting. Diarrheal type: toxin produced in vivo after ingestion causes later-onset watery diarrhea and cramping.", "additionalNotes": "Clinically and historically often misdiagnosed as Staphylococcal food poisoning (emetic form) or Clostridium perfringens food poisoning (diarrheal form) due to overlapping presentation."}, {"id": "c_tetani", "scientificName": "Clostridium tetani", "classificationPath": "Gram-Positive Rods > Spore-forming > Anaerobic > Clostridium", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Rods, spore-forming", "arrangement": "Single rods", "oxygenRequirement": "Strict anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Spore germinates in tissue under low-oxygen conditions", "Found widely in soil and animal/human intestine (especially horses)"], "virulenceFactors": ["Tetanospasmin (tetanus toxin) — exotoxin that binds ganglioside receptors and blocks release of inhibitory neurotransmitters (glycine and GABA) at spinal synapses"], "diseases": ["Tetanus (lockjaw) — rigid paralysis, extreme muscle spasms"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis based on classic presentation; organism rarely recovered from wound cultures"], "examPearls": ["Dirty puncture wound is the classic exposure", "Mechanism = BLOCKS INHIBITORY neurotransmitters → unopposed muscle contraction → RIGID/spastic paralysis (opposite mechanism to botulinum, which blocks excitatory ACh release → FLACCID paralysis)", "Prevention is via tetanus toxoid vaccine (inactivated toxin)"], "reservoir": "Soil; intestines of humans and animals, especially horses", "transmission": "Spores enter through puncture wounds, burns, or umbilical stump of newborns (neonatal tetanus)", "detailedPathogenesis": "Spores germinate in anaerobic/low-oxygen wound tissue (e.g., deep puncture, devitalized tissue). As bacteria die/lyse, tetanospasmin is released, travels retrograde along motor neurons to the spinal cord, and blocks release of inhibitory neurotransmitters glycine and GABA at inhibitory synapses. This removes normal inhibition of motor neurons, causing sustained, unopposed muscle contraction — classically presenting as trismus (lockjaw); can progress to respiratory muscle involvement and death from asphyxiation.", "additionalNotes": "Incubation period approximately 4-10 days. Prevention: thorough wound cleaning, leaving wounds open to air, tetanus toxoid vaccination (active immunization using inactivated toxin)."}, {"id": "c_botulinum", "scientificName": "Clostridium botulinum", "classificationPath": "Gram-Positive Rods > Spore-forming > Anaerobic > Clostridium", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Rods, spore-forming", "arrangement": "Single rods", "oxygenRequirement": "Strict anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Found in soil, water, animal large intestine", "Spores survive in improperly canned/preserved food, especially low-acid home-canned vegetables and meats"], "virulenceFactors": ["Botulinum toxin — A-B polypeptide neurotoxin, heat-labile (destroyed in 10 min at 60°C); blocks acetylcholine release at the neuromuscular junction"], "diseases": ["Foodborne botulism — reversible flaccid paralysis from preformed toxin in food", "Floppy baby syndrome — infant botulism with flaccid paralysis (from ingested spores germinating in infant gut, e.g., honey)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis; toxin can be detected in food/serum/stool"], "examPearls": ["Classic source: home-canned ALKALINE vegetables (low-acid canning is the danger zone)", "Mechanism = BLOCKS EXCITATORY acetylcholine release → FLACCID paralysis (opposite of tetanus)", "Toxin is heat-LABILE — proper cooking/reheating of canned food destroys it (100°C for 10 minutes)", "Bulging or leaking cans should never be eaten"], "reservoir": "Soil, water, animal intestine (especially large intestine)", "transmission": "Ingestion of preformed toxin in improperly canned or preserved food; spores in honey (infant botulism)", "detailedPathogenesis": "Spores contaminate food (vegetables, meat), survive initial canning, then germinate in the anaerobic, sealed environment of the can/jar while awaiting distribution. Vegetative cells produce potent neurotoxin. Ingested toxin blocks acetylcholine release at neuromuscular junctions, causing symmetric descending flaccid paralysis — blurred/double vision, difficulty swallowing/speaking, progressing to respiratory failure if untreated. Onset 12-36 hours after ingestion.", "additionalNotes": "Prevention: proper canning technique, discard cans/jars that are bulging, leaking, or have off taste/smell; boil home-canned food at 100°C for at least 10 minutes before eating to destroy any preformed toxin."}, {"id": "c_perfringens", "scientificName": "Clostridium perfringens", "classificationPath": "Gram-Positive Rods > Spore-forming > Anaerobic > Clostridium", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Rods, spore-forming", "arrangement": "Single rods", "oxygenRequirement": "Strict anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Found widely in soil, animal feces, vegetation, human/animal intestine", "Hemolytic on blood agar"], "virulenceFactors": ["Alpha-toxin and other tissue-destroying enzymes causing hemolysis and gas formation in tissue", "Enterotoxin (food poisoning form)"], "diseases": ["Gas gangrene (clostridial myonecrosis) — contaminated traumatic wound; pain, edema, gas, fever, tachycardia", "Food poisoning — reheated meats, noninflammatory diarrhea, incubation 8-24 hours"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-positive anaerobic spore-forming rod recovered from wound or stool", "Crepitus (crackling) on palpation of infected tissue indicates gas production"], "examPearls": ["Gas gangrene: contaminated wound + dead/devitalized tissue (low oxygen) = perfect growth conditions", "Crepitus on exam = gas in tissue = classic exam finding", "Food poisoning: classic vehicle is reheated meats (spores survive cooking, germinate on standing, toxin forms)", "C. novyi and C. septicum are less common causes of gas gangrene"], "reservoir": "Soil, skin, intestine, vagina (spores widespread in environment)", "transmission": "Traumatic wound implantation (gas gangrene); foodborne (reheated meat, food poisoning)", "detailedPathogenesis": "Gas gangrene: spores contaminate a wound with necrotic, poorly perfused (low-oxygen) tissue — ideal anaerobic growth conditions. Toxins destroy red blood cells and tissue, producing gas within tissue (palpable crepitus), dark discoloration, and foul odor. Food poisoning: spores survive cooking, germinate during improper food storage (reheated meats), proliferate, and produce enterotoxin causing cramping and watery diarrhea.", "additionalNotes": "Food poisoning incubation roughly 8-24 hours, distinguishing it from the faster S. aureus and B. cereus emetic syndromes."}, {"id": "c_difficile", "scientificName": "Clostridium difficile", "classificationPath": "Gram-Positive Rods > Spore-forming > Anaerobic > Clostridium", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Rods, spore-forming", "arrangement": "Single rods", "oxygenRequirement": "Strict anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Overgrows in colon after normal flora disrupted by antibiotics"], "virulenceFactors": ["Toxin A and Toxin B — disrupt colonic epithelial cells, cause inflammation"], "diseases": ["Antibiotic-associated diarrhea and colitis", "Pseudomembranous colitis — yellow plaques (pseudomembranes) on colon"], "labDiagnosis": ["Stool toxin assay (Toxin A/B detection) or PCR; pseudomembranes seen on colonoscopy"], "examPearls": ["Classic trigger antibiotics: clindamycin, cephalosporins, amoxicillin, ampicillin", "Hospitalized patient on antibiotics with new diarrhea = think C. difficile", "Pseudomembranous colitis = yellow plaques on colonoscopy is the classic finding"], "reservoir": "Can be part of normal GI flora in small numbers; hospital environment reservoir for spores", "transmission": "Endogenous overgrowth after antibiotic disruption of normal flora; spores can spread person-to-person in hospital settings", "predisposingFactors": ["Recent or ongoing antibiotic therapy, especially clindamycin, cephalosporins, amoxicillin, ampicillin", "Hospitalization"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Antibiotics disrupt normal protective colonic flora, allowing C. difficile (resistant to the antibiotic in use) to overgrow. Toxin A and B damage colonic epithelium, causing inflammation that can range from mild diarrhea to severe pseudomembranous colitis, characterized by yellow-white plaques (pseudomembranes) composed of fibrin, mucus, and inflammatory cells on the colonic mucosa."}, {"id": "l_monocytogenes", "scientificName": "Listeria monocytogenes", "classificationPath": "Gram-Positive Rods > Non-spore-forming > Beta-hemolytic, motile, cold-growth", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Rods, slightly swollen in the middle", "arrangement": "Single cells or short chains", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe; facultative intracellular pathogen", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Beta-hemolytic — resembles beta-hemolytic streptococcus on blood agar", "Motile (tumbling motility)", "Grows at cold temperatures (cold enrichment) — unusual among bacterial pathogens", "Non-spore-forming"], "virulenceFactors": ["Listeriolysin O — a beta-hemolysin that facilitates rapid escape from the phagosome into host cell cytoplasm"], "diseases": ["Neonatal septicemia and meningitis — 3rd most common cause", "Meningitis in renal transplant or cancer patients — most common cause in these populations", "General listeriosis — fever, diarrhea, sore throat (mild in healthy adults)", "Miscarriage/preterm birth if infection occurs during pregnancy (transplacental transmission)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Beta-hemolytic gram-positive rod, motile, grows at refrigeration temperatures (cold enrichment culture technique)"], "examPearls": ["Facultative INTRACELLULAR — escapes phagosome via listeriolysin O, allowing cell-to-cell spread without ever leaving cytoplasm", "Classic exposure: unpasteurized dairy, deli meats/cold cuts", "One of the few bacteria that grows well at refrigerator temperatures", "Special concern in pregnancy — can cross placenta, causing miscarriage or neonatal infection", "Immunologic immaturity (neonates) or impaired cell-mediated immunity (transplant/cancer patients) predisposes to severe disease"], "reservoir": "Soil, water, plants, animals; contaminated/decaying soil and water serve as environmental reservoirs", "transmission": "Foodborne — deli foods, unpasteurized milk products; transplacental (mother to fetus)", "predisposingFactors": ["Pregnancy", "Neonates (immunologic immaturity)", "Renal transplant", "Cancer/immunosuppression"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Ingested bacteria invade intestinal epithelium and are taken up by macrophages; listeriolysin O allows escape from the phagosome into the cytoplasm before lysosomal killing occurs, enabling intracellular survival and replication. The bacteria can then spread cell-to-cell, evading humoral immunity — explaining why cell-mediated immunity (which fights intracellular pathogens) is the key host defense, and why immunocompromised hosts (impaired cell-mediated immunity) suffer severe disease.", "additionalNotes": "Prevention: heat-treat foods suspected of contamination with sewage or animal feces; avoid unpasteurized dairy and undercooked deli meats, especially during pregnancy."}, {"id": "e_rhusiopathiae", "scientificName": "Erysipelothrix rhusiopathiae", "classificationPath": "Gram-Positive Rods > Non-spore-forming > Zoonotic (pig-associated)", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Rods", "arrangement": "Single/short chains", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Normal flora of pig tonsils", "Survives long periods in the environment"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not well characterized in source material; causes localized cutaneous inflammation"], "diseases": ["Erysipeloid — occupational skin infection with inflammation, swelling, itching at site of entry"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis based on occupational exposure history and characteristic lesion"], "examPearls": ["Classic occupation: slaughterhouse workers, fishermen, others handling animals/fish", "Entry via scratches/abrasions on hands and arms", "Primarily a veterinary/zoonotic pathogen with occasional occupational human disease"], "reservoir": "Normal flora of pig tonsils; widely distributed among vertebrate animals", "transmission": "Occupational exposure — enters through skin scratches/abrasions from contact with infected animals", "predisposingFactors": ["Occupational animal contact (slaughterhouse, fishing industry)"], "additionalNotes": "Causes occasional disease outbreaks in animals; in humans, disease is localized to skin (erysipeloid) rather than systemic in most cases."}, {"id": "c_diphtheriae", "scientificName": "Corynebacterium diphtheriae", "classificationPath": "Gram-Positive Rods > Non-spore-forming > Club-shaped", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Slender rods with club-shaped (swollen) end", "arrangement": "V or L shapes (palisades)", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Gray-to-black colonies", "Club-shaped gram-positive rods in V or L arrangement on Gram stain", "Toxin production requires lysogenic phage (toxin gene is phage-encoded)"], "virulenceFactors": ["Diphtheria toxin (A-B exotoxin) — produced only by lysogenized strains; inhibits protein synthesis by ADP-ribosylating elongation factor eEF-2; damages heart and nerve tissue"], "diseases": ["Diphtheria — pharyngeal/respiratory infection with gray pseudomembrane causing airway obstruction", "Bull neck (massive cervical lymphadenopathy/edema)", "Myocarditis and nerve palsies from systemic toxin effects"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram stain shows club-shaped rods in V/L palisade arrangement", "Culture on selective media (e.g., Loeffler's, tellurite); toxin detection (Elek test)"], "examPearls": ["Toxin production REQUIRES lysogenic conversion by a bacteriophage carrying the tox gene — non-lysogenized strains are non-toxigenic", "Gray pseudomembrane in the throat is pathognomonic; scraping it off causes bleeding", "Bull neck + myocarditis + nerve palsies = classic triad of severe diphtheria", "Toxin mechanism (ADP-ribosylation of eEF-2, blocking protein synthesis) is IDENTICAL to Pseudomonas exotoxin A"], "reservoir": "Humans (asymptomatic carriers and patients)", "transmission": "Respiratory droplets; contact with skin lesions", "detailedPathogenesis": "Bacteria colonize the nasopharynx, oropharynx, larynx, or trachea mucosa. Toxin secretion causes epithelial cell death, producing a dense fibrinosuppurative exudate with necrosis that appears as a gray-black pseudomembrane. Histologically: neutrophilic infiltration beneath the necrotic area, tissue swelling, fibrin exudation. Removing the membrane causes bleeding. The membrane can mechanically obstruct the airway. Absorbed toxin also causes fatty change and necrosis of cardiac muscle, peripheral neuritis, and fatty change in liver, kidney, and adrenal glands.", "additionalNotes": "Vaccination (DTaP/Tdap) with diphtheria toxoid is the primary prevention strategy."}, {"id": "p_acnes", "scientificName": "Propionibacterium acnes", "classificationPath": "Gram-Positive Rods > Non-spore-forming > Anaerobic, no mycolic acid", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Rods, similar appearance to Corynebacterium", "arrangement": "Single/short chains", "oxygenRequirement": "Anaerobic (tolerates anaerobic conditions better than Corynebacterium)", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Cell wall lacks mycolic acid (unlike Mycobacterium/Nocardia)", "Found on skin at sebaceous glands"], "virulenceFactors": ["Lipase activity contributing to local inflammation in hair follicles"], "diseases": ["Acne vulgaris — contributing factor, especially in adolescents (multifactorial disease also involving genetics, hormones, skin structure)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Anaerobic gram-positive rod isolated from skin/sebaceous gland specimens"], "examPearls": ["A contributing — not sole — cause of acne; works alongside hormonal and genetic factors", "Differentiated from Corynebacterium by anaerobic tolerance and absence of mycolic acid in cell wall"], "reservoir": "Human skin, particularly sebaceous gland-rich areas", "transmission": "Endogenous skin flora", "additionalNotes": "Acne pathogenesis is multifactorial: genetic predisposition, hormonal changes (especially adolescence), skin structure, and bacterial colonization/inflammation all contribute."}, {"id": "m_tuberculosis", "scientificName": "Mycobacterium tuberculosis", "classificationPath": "Acid-Fast > Mycobacterium > Cultivable", "gramReaction": "Does not Gram stain reliably (acid-fast stain used instead)", "morphology": "Rods", "arrangement": "Single/clumped", "oxygenRequirement": "Obligate aerobe; facultative intracellular", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Acid-fast bacilli (auramine-rhodamine staining for screening; Ziehl-Neelsen for confirmation)", "Produces niacin", "Heat-sensitive catalase", "Slow grower — generation time ~12-24 hours; colonies visible in 2-60 days depending on species", "Grows on lipid-rich media (Lowenstein-Jensen, Ogawa) with egg yolk, glycerol, malachite green"], "virulenceFactors": ["Sulfatides (sulfolipids in cell envelope) — inhibit phagosome-lysosome fusion, allowing intracellular survival; if fusion does occur, the waxy mycolic acid coat reduces killing", "Cord factor (trehalose dimycolate) — causes serpentine growth in vitro; inhibits leukocyte migration; disrupts mitochondrial respiration and oxidative phosphorylation", "Tuberculin (surface protein) plus mycolic acid — triggers delayed-type hypersensitivity and cell-mediated immunity; mediates granuloma and caseation formation"], "diseases": ["Primary tuberculosis — initial infection, often subclinical or low-grade fever; Ghon complex (calcified primary lesion) on imaging", "Secondary (reactivation) tuberculosis — recurrence with severe cough, hemoptysis, fever, chest pain, weight loss when immunity wanes", "Extrapulmonary tuberculosis — spread to lymph nodes, kidney, bone/joints, reproductive organs, brain (meninges)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Tuberculin skin test (PPD) — delayed-type hypersensitivity test", "Chest X-ray (Ghon complex, cavitary lesions)", "Acid-fast staining of sputum or other specimens", "Culture on lipid-rich media (slow growth, 2-60 days)"], "examPearls": ["Ghon complex = caseous necrotic lesion + calcification, visible on chest X-ray, marks primary infection", "High-risk patient profile: poverty, HIV-positive, IV drug user", "Facultative intracellular pathogen surviving inside macrophages via sulfatide-mediated phagosome-lysosome fusion inhibition", "Cell-mediated immunity (not antibody) is the key host response — explains granuloma/caseation and why immunosuppression (HIV) drives reactivation", "BCG vaccine used for prevention in some countries"], "reservoir": "Humans (chronic carriers, active disease)", "transmission": "Airborne — inhalation of droplet nuclei from coughing patients", "predisposingFactors": ["Poverty/crowding", "HIV infection", "IV drug use", "Immunosuppression"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Inhaled bacteria reach alveoli and are phagocytosed by macrophages but survive and multiply intracellularly due to sulfatide-mediated inhibition of phagosome-lysosome fusion. After 3-4 weeks, cell-mediated immunity develops, forming a tubercle (granuloma) — a nodule containing bacteria, macrophages, surrounded by lymphocytes, neutrophils, and fibroblasts. The tubercle may become a caseous (cheese-like) necrotic lesion; if calcified, it is termed the Ghon complex, detectable on X-ray. A softened tubercle that develops an air-filled cavity (tubercle cavity) allows further bacterial spread. In secondary disease, dormant bacteria reactivate when host immunity weakens, causing severe symptomatic disease with productive cough, hemoptysis. Extrapulmonary spread during the secondary phase can seed lymph nodes, kidneys, bones/joints, reproductive organs, and meninges.", "additionalNotes": "Diagnosis pathway: (1) tuberculin skin test, (2) chest X-ray, (3) acid-fast staining of sputum. Disease classified for reporting purposes as pulmonary (sputum-positive or sputum-negative) versus extrapulmonary TB. Control relies on early diagnosis/treatment of active cases to prevent transmission; BCG vaccine used in some national programs."}, {"id": "m_leprae", "scientificName": "Mycobacterium leprae", "classificationPath": "Acid-Fast > Mycobacterium > Non-cultivable", "gramReaction": "Acid-fast (does not Gram stain)", "morphology": "Acid-fast rods", "arrangement": "Single/clumped", "oxygenRequirement": "Obligate intracellular parasite", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Cannot be cultured in vitro on any artificial medium — the only Mycobacterium species with this property", "Optimal growth at temperatures below normal body temperature", "Acid-fast"], "virulenceFactors": ["Obligate intracellular survival within macrophages and Schwann cells; preferentially infects cooler body sites"], "diseases": ["Leprosy (Hansen's disease) — chronic infection of skin and peripheral nerves", "Tuberculoid (neural) leprosy — mild, non-progressive form from strong delayed-type hypersensitivity response; few organisms detectable, but nerve damage causes numbness", "Lepromatous (progressive) leprosy — severe disseminated form with thick, nodular facial/ear skin ('leonine facies'); weak cell-mediated immune response allows extensive bacterial growth and tissue destruction", "Borderline leprosy — intermediate, unpredictable course between the two poles"], "labDiagnosis": ["Acid-fast staining of skin scrapings/biopsy; cannot be cultured — clinical and histopathological diagnosis required"], "examPearls": ["Only Mycobacterium that cannot be grown in any artificial culture medium", "Prefers cooler body sites — skin, mucous membranes, peripheral nerves (explains the classic distribution of lesions)", "Tuberculoid (strong CMI, few organisms, nerve damage) vs Lepromatous (weak CMI, many organisms, disfiguring skin disease) represents a spectrum driven by host immune response, not just bacterial factors", "Long-standing disease can lead to disabling deformities: blindness, absorption/shortening of digits, sensory loss leading to repeated unnoticed injury"], "reservoir": "Humans (primary reservoir); some evidence of animal reservoirs (e.g., armadillos) outside this course's source material", "transmission": "Prolonged skin-to-skin contact, inhalation of nasal/respiratory secretions, possibly insect vectors", "detailedPathogenesis": "Bacteria are taken up by macrophages; most exposed individuals successfully clear or contain the infection via macrophage killing. In susceptible hosts, disease manifests along a spectrum determined by host cell-mediated immune response. Tuberculoid form: strong delayed-type hypersensitivity localizes infection to a few firm, raised lesions with nerve damage and sensory loss but few detectable organisms. Lepromatous form: weak cell-mediated immunity allows widespread bacterial proliferation in skin, producing thickened, nodular, disfiguring lesions (especially face/ears) and eventual peripheral nerve destruction leading to motor and sensory loss in hands and feet (clawing, ulceration, bone resorption causing digit shortening).", "additionalNotes": "First described in 1873. Disease is most common in tropical/subtropical regions."}, {"id": "nocardia", "scientificName": "Nocardia asteroides and Nocardia brasiliensis", "classificationPath": "Branching Filamentous Rods > Partially Acid-Fast > Aerobic", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Filaments breaking up into rods", "arrangement": "Branching filaments", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Partially acid-fast — some smear areas stain blue, some red (modified acid-fast stain)", "Gram-positive filamentous bacilli"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed in source material; cell wall mycolic acid content contributes to partial acid-fastness and resistance to killing"], "diseases": ["Cavitary bronchopulmonary disease", "Mycetoma", "Hematogenous spread to brain (brain abscess)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Modified acid-fast stain (partial acid-fastness, distinguishing from fully acid-fast Mycobacterium and non-acid-fast Actinomyces)"], "examPearls": ["Partially acid-fast is the key distinguishing lab feature — separates Nocardia from both Mycobacterium (fully acid-fast) and Actinomyces (non-acid-fast)", "Immunosuppression and cancer predispose to pulmonary infection", "Can spread hematogenously to the brain, causing abscess — important in immunocompromised patients with pulmonary nocardiosis"], "reservoir": "Soil and decaying organic matter (environmental saprophyte)", "transmission": "Inhalation primarily; occasionally direct skin inoculation (mycetoma)", "predisposingFactors": ["Immunosuppression", "Cancer"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Inhaled organisms can cause chronic, cavitary pulmonary infection resembling tuberculosis. In immunocompromised hosts, hematogenous dissemination can seed the brain, forming abscesses. Cutaneous inoculation (e.g., through skin trauma in soil-exposed individuals) can lead to mycetoma — chronic, progressive, destructive subcutaneous infection."}, {"id": "a_israelii", "scientificName": "Actinomyces israelii", "classificationPath": "Branching Filamentous Rods > Non-acid-fast > Anaerobic", "gramReaction": "Gram-positive", "morphology": "Branching rods, breaking into fragments", "arrangement": "Branching filaments", "oxygenRequirement": "Anaerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Non-acid-fast (distinguishes from Nocardia)", "Branching rods", "Sulfur granules visible in pus (microcolonies of the organism)"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed; opportunistic invasion following mucosal/dental trauma"], "diseases": ["Cervicofacial actinomycosis ('lumpy jaw') — following dental trauma or poor oral hygiene", "Mycetoma-like lesions on the jaw line", "Pelvic actinomycosis associated with IUD use"], "labDiagnosis": ["Sulfur granules in pus; anaerobic culture shows gram-positive, non-acid-fast branching rods"], "examPearls": ["Normal flora of gingival crevices and female genital tract — disease occurs when normal mucosal barriers are breached", "'Lumpy jaw' from dental trauma/poor oral hygiene is the classic presentation", "IUD use is a classic risk factor for pelvic actinomycosis", "Non-acid-fast is the key feature distinguishing it from Nocardia"], "reservoir": "Normal flora of human gingival crevices, tonsils, and female genital tract", "transmission": "Endogenous — invades through breaks in mucosa from dental trauma, extraction, or IUD-related changes", "predisposingFactors": ["Poor oral hygiene/dental disease", "Dental extraction", "IUD use"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Normally harmless oral/genital flora; becomes pathogenic when mucosal integrity is breached (dental trauma, extraction) allowing invasion into deeper tissue. Forms slowly progressive, indurated swelling with draining sinus tracts; pus contains characteristic 'sulfur granules' (yellow microcolonies of bacterial filaments). Most cases remain localized; rarely spreads systemically except in patients with poor overall health.", "additionalNotes": "Treatment: surgical drainage of abscess/pus combined with antibiotics."}, {"id": "n_meningitidis", "scientificName": "Neisseria meningitidis (meningococcus)", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Cocci > Neisseria > Maltose fermenter", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Kidney bean-shaped diplococci (flat sides touching)", "arrangement": "Diplococci", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic; fastidious (requires enriched media)", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Ferments maltose (unlike N. gonorrhoeae)", "Large polysaccharide capsule", "Grows on chocolate agar in 5% CO2 atmosphere (does not grow well on blood agar)", "Identified in CSF via latex particle agglutination against capsular antigens"], "virulenceFactors": ["Pili — organ of adherence to non-ciliated epithelial cells of the nasopharynx", "Polysaccharide capsule — antiphagocytic; at least 13 serogroups (A, B, C, D, X, Y, Z, E, W-135, H, I, K, L); A, B, C, Y, W-135 are most pathogenic in humans", "Endotoxin (lipopolysaccharide, LPS) — exceptionally high potency; triggers fever, shock, and disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) more readily than other gram-negative endotoxins"], "diseases": ["Meningitis — bacterial meningitis in children over age 2", "Meningococcemia (meningococcal septicemia) — petechial rash, can progress to purpura", "Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome — bilateral adrenal hemorrhage causing acute adrenal insufficiency and shock"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative diplococci on Gram stain of CSF", "Culture on chocolate agar, 5% CO2", "Latex particle agglutination for capsular antigen detection in CSF", "Maltose fermentation positive (distinguishes from gonococcus)"], "examPearls": ["Maltose fermentation is THE classic biochemical test separating N. meningitidis from N. gonorrhoeae", "Transmission via respiratory droplets; colonizes nasopharynx/oropharynx before invading bloodstream", "Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome = petechiae/purpura + DIC + bilateral adrenal hemorrhage + shock — classic severe presentation", "Endotoxin potency is unusually high among gram-negatives, explaining rapid, severe presentation", "Death can occur within hours of symptom onset in fulminant meningococcemia"], "reservoir": "Human nasopharynx (asymptomatic carriage common)", "transmission": "Respiratory droplets; oropharyngeal colonization with later hematogenous spread to meninges", "detailedPathogenesis": "Pili mediate attachment to non-ciliated nasopharyngeal epithelial cells; the organism invades the submucosa, multiplies over 18-24 hours, and can enter the bloodstream. The antiphagocytic capsule allows survival despite macrophage encounter. Endotoxin (LPS) release triggers massive cytokine release (TNF, IL-1, IL-6, eicosanoids, platelet activating factor), causing severe systemic inflammation, capillary leak, and disseminated intravascular coagulation — producing the characteristic petechial/purpuric rash. Organisms crossing the blood-brain barrier reach the pia mater and cause purulent meningitis with marked neutrophilic infiltration of the subarachnoid space, potentially leading to neuronal damage and brain death. In meningococcemia, the rapid, severe disease course (death possible within 6-24 hours) reflects the unusually high potency of meningococcal endotoxin; complications include myocarditis, pulmonary edema/pleuritis, renal failure, and Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome (adrenal hemorrhage from DIC).", "additionalNotes": "Major public health concern especially in developing countries due to ease of transmission and rapid fatality; vaccine availability and carrier control remain challenges for elimination."}, {"id": "n_gonorrhoeae", "scientificName": "Neisseria gonorrhoeae (gonococcus)", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Cocci > Neisseria > Maltose non-fermenter", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Kidney bean-shaped diplococci", "arrangement": "Diplococci, often seen intracellularly within neutrophils", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic; fastidious", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Does NOT ferment maltose (distinguishes from N. meningitidis)", "Intracellular gram-negative diplococci visible within PMNs on urethral smear", "Requires enriched media (chocolate agar, Thayer-Martin)"], "virulenceFactors": ["Pili for adherence", "Outer membrane proteins aiding immune evasion (antigenic variation)"], "diseases": ["Gonorrhea — urethritis in men (dysuria, purulent discharge); variable presentation in women from asymptomatic to pelvic inflammatory disease (PID)", "PID complications — ectopic pregnancy, infertility", "Disseminated gonococcal infection — septic arthritis, skin petechiae", "Gonococcal ophthalmia neonatorum — neonatal eye infection acquired during birth through infected birth canal; can cause blindness from corneal scarring if untreated"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram stain: intracellular gram-negative diplococci within neutrophils from urethral discharge", "Culture on Thayer-Martin or chocolate agar", "Maltose fermentation negative (distinguishes from meningococcus)"], "examPearls": ["Maltose-NEGATIVE — the opposite biochemical pattern from N. meningitidis", "Women often asymptomatic — serve as reservoir for transmission while at risk for silent PID", "Ophthalmia neonatorum prevention: 1% silver nitrate, erythromycin, or tetracycline applied to newborn eyes at birth", "Sexually transmitted — classic STI presentation"], "reservoir": "Humans only", "transmission": "Sexual contact; neonatal transmission during vaginal delivery", "detailedPathogenesis": "Attaches to urogenital epithelium via pili; invades and triggers local neutrophilic inflammatory response, producing purulent discharge. In women, ascending infection can reach the fallopian tubes/pelvis causing PID, with subsequent risk of tubal scarring (ectopic pregnancy, infertility). Bloodstream dissemination can cause septic arthritis and skin lesions. Neonatal ophthalmia occurs when the infant passes through an infected birth canal, causing conjunctival inflammation, swelling, and purulent discharge; corneal scarring from untreated infection can cause blindness.", "additionalNotes": "Best prevention for neonatal disease is prompt prophylactic eye treatment at birth in regions/populations with significant maternal gonorrhea prevalence."}, {"id": "m_catarrhalis", "scientificName": "Moraxella catarrhalis", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Cocci > Close relative of Neisseria", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Diplococcus", "arrangement": "Diplococci", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Close relative of Neisseria genus", "Normal upper respiratory tract flora"], "virulenceFactors": ["Endotoxin — may contribute to disease pathology"], "diseases": ["Otitis media", "Sinusitis", "Bronchitis and bronchopneumonia in elderly patients with COPD"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative diplococcus, distinguished from Neisseria species by biochemical testing and clinical context"], "examPearls": ["Classic COPD-related respiratory pathogen in elderly patients", "Part of normal respiratory flora that can become pathogenic in compromised hosts"], "reservoir": "Normal upper respiratory tract flora", "transmission": "Respiratory droplets", "predisposingFactors": ["COPD", "Elderly age"]}, {"id": "p_aeruginosa", "scientificName": "Pseudomonas aeruginosa", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Aerobic > Oxidase (+)", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Bacillus (rod)", "arrangement": "Single rods", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Oxidase positive", "Blue-green pigment (pyocyanin) production", "Fruity/grape-like odor", "Single polar flagellum", "Tolerant of soap, disinfectants, heat, cold, drying — survives well in hospital environment"], "virulenceFactors": ["Exotoxin A — ADP-ribosylates eEF-2, inhibiting protein synthesis (same mechanism as diphtheria toxin)", "Various proteases (e.g., elastase) and other enzymes facilitating tissue invasion"], "diseases": ["Burn wound infections — blue-green pus, fruity odor", "Pneumonia — especially in cystic fibrosis or chronic granulomatous disease patients", "UTI — particularly in catheterized patients", "Otitis externa ('swimmer's ear'), eye infections", "Hospital-acquired/nosocomial infections broadly"], "labDiagnosis": ["Oxidase positive, gram-negative aerobic rod", "Blue-green pigmented colonies with fruity odor on culture"], "examPearls": ["Exotoxin A mechanism is IDENTICAL to diphtheria toxin (ADP-ribosylation of eEF-2) — high-yield comparison point", "Classic burn-unit and CF/immunocompromised pathogen", "Notorious environmental survivor — found in moist hospital environments (sinks, respiratory equipment), driving nosocomial infections", "Blue-green pigment + fruity odor = pathognomonic bedside clue"], "reservoir": "Soil and water; found in ~10% of normal human intestine; occasionally saliva or moist skin", "transmission": "Environmental exposure; nosocomial spread via contaminated equipment/surfaces", "predisposingFactors": ["Burns", "Cystic fibrosis", "Chronic granulomatous disease", "Urinary catheterization", "Immunosuppression"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Opportunistic pathogen rarely causing disease in healthy individuals; thrives when normal barriers are breached (burned skin) or host defenses are impaired (CF, chronic granulomatous disease, immunosuppression). Once established in tissue, it produces exotoxin A and various enzymes that destroy host cells and facilitate further invasion and spread, contributing to severe and difficult-to-treat infections."}, {"id": "b_pseudomallei", "scientificName": "Burkholderia pseudomallei", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Aerobic > Oxidase (+) > Reclassified from Pseudomonas", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod with bipolar staining (stains darker at both ends)", "arrangement": "Single rods", "oxygenRequirement": "Strict aerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Bipolar staining pattern", "Musty/earthy odor on culture", "Colonies initially smooth, shiny, white; become wrinkled, dry, cream-colored, button-like center with prolonged incubation", "Formerly classified as Pseudomonas pseudomallei; reclassified to new genus Burkholderia based on genetic differences"], "virulenceFactors": ["Intracellular survival capability; specific toxin/virulence profile not detailed extensively in source material"], "diseases": ["Melioidosis — highly variable presentation", "Acute septicemic form — high mortality, sudden severe septic shock", "Chronic localized form — pulmonary disease resembling tuberculosis (often misdiagnosed as TB that fails anti-TB therapy)", "Abscesses in various organs (liver, spleen, brain), suppurative arthritis", "Cutaneous chronic ulcers/subcutaneous abscesses"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative rod with bipolar staining, distinctive musty odor, characteristic colony morphology evolving over 24-48+ hours of incubation"], "examPearls": ["Endemic to Southeast Asia (Thailand, Myanmar, Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam, Malaysia, etc.) and northern Australia, between 20°N and 20°S latitude", "Classic Thai association: most common in the Northeast region (Khon Kaen province), especially during rainy season", "Famous historical link: U.S. soldiers in Vietnam War exposed via helicopter-disturbed soil dust", "45-80% of patients have an underlying predisposing disease (diabetes, cirrhosis, blood disorders) that impairs immunity", "Often mimics tuberculosis clinically and radiographically — consider in 'TB' patients not responding to anti-TB treatment", "Three clinical patterns: asymptomatic seroconversion, chronic/subacute localized disease, and acute septicemia (near 100% mortality if untreated, especially in immunocompromised patients)"], "reservoir": "Soil and stagnant water, particularly in tropical latitudes between 20°N and 20°S", "transmission": "Primarily inhalation of contaminated soil dust; also through skin wounds/burns; possible sexual transmission (isolated from urine and vaginal secretions); not established to spread via food", "predisposingFactors": ["Diabetes mellitus", "Cirrhosis", "Hematologic disorders", "Other immunocompromising conditions"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Most human infection results from inhalation of bacteria-laden soil dust, consistent with the high rate of pulmonary involvement (most common organ affected). Disease course is highly variable: many exposed individuals develop only asymptomatic seroconversion; others develop chronic localized disease (pulmonary lesions resembling TB, or localized skin/organ abscesses) that may persist for months to years; a subset — particularly those with underlying immunocompromising disease — progress to fulminant acute septicemia with an extremely high mortality rate.", "additionalNotes": "Disease is also called melioidosis; the organism's pattern of intracellular survival in chronic disease (few organisms detectable in chronic lesions despite ongoing disease) is notable."}, {"id": "acinetobacter", "scientificName": "Acinetobacter spp. (A. baumannii / A. lwoffi)", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Aerobic > Coccobacilli, Neisseria-like", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Coccobacilli, sometimes elongating to rod form on culture media", "arrangement": "Mostly in pairs, resembling Neisseria", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Coccobacillary, gram-negative — resembles Neisseria morphologically but distinguished by culture/biochemical testing", "Two historically named varieties: Acinetobacter calcoaceticus subsp. anitratus (now renamed Acinetobacter baumannii) and subsp. lwoffii"], "virulenceFactors": ["Notable intrinsic and acquired antibiotic resistance contributing to its role as a hospital pathogen"], "diseases": ["Nosocomial infections — most common setting for clinically significant disease", "Bacteremia — occurs in ~5% of infections and is an important cause of mortality"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative coccobacilli resembling Neisseria but distinguished by rod-form colony morphology and lack of maltose/glucose fermentation pattern typical of Neisseria"], "examPearls": ["A. anitratus was renamed Acinetobacter baumannii — now a notorious multidrug-resistant hospital pathogen worldwide", "Morphologically mimics Neisseria — a common source of diagnostic confusion", "One of the most common causes of hospital-acquired infection generally"], "reservoir": "Water, soil; occasionally found on human skin/body", "transmission": "Nosocomial spread, especially in ICU settings via contaminated equipment/surfaces", "predisposingFactors": ["Hospitalization, especially ICU admission", "Invasive devices"]}, {"id": "brucella", "scientificName": "Brucella spp. (B. abortus, B. melitensis, B. suis)", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Aerobic > Zoonotic (cattle/goat/swine)", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Small coccobacilli/rods", "arrangement": "Single/small groups", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Species differentiated by animal host of origin: B. abortus (cattle/buffalo), B. melitensis (goats/sheep), B. suis (pigs)"], "virulenceFactors": ["Facultative intracellular survival in host reticuloendothelial cells (implied by chronic relapsing disease course)"], "diseases": ["Brucellosis — zoonotic disease transmitted from animals to humans; ranges from asymptomatic to acute illness with high fever, chills, headache, myalgia, fatigue, dizziness, weight loss"], "labDiagnosis": ["Blood culture (requires extended incubation); serology"], "examPearls": ["Classic occupational exposure: slaughterhouse workers, livestock handlers", "Also transmitted via unpasteurized milk/dairy from infected animals", "Incubation period 6-14 days; presentation ranges from asymptomatic to severe febrile illness", "Treatment requires prolonged antibiotic courses due to intracellular persistence"], "reservoir": "Cattle/water buffalo (B. abortus), goats/sheep (B. melitensis), pigs (B. suis)", "transmission": "Direct contact with infected animal tissues/fluids; ingestion of unpasteurized milk/dairy products", "predisposingFactors": ["Occupational animal exposure (slaughterhouse, farming)"], "additionalNotes": "Most prevalent in Europe, Africa, India, and Mexico per source material. Prevention: vaccinate livestock, cull infected animals. Treatment requires prolonged antibiotic therapy."}, {"id": "b_pertussis", "scientificName": "Bordetella pertussis", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Aerobic > Small rods", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Small rods", "arrangement": "Single/pairs", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Small gram-negative rods; fastidious growth requirements"], "virulenceFactors": ["Filamentous hemagglutinin and pertussis toxin (components of acellular vaccine)"], "diseases": ["Pertussis (whooping cough) — classic three-stage respiratory illness in unvaccinated children"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis based on characteristic cough pattern; culture/PCR from nasopharyngeal specimens"], "examPearls": ["Classic exposure: unvaccinated child (immigrant family or religious vaccine objection)", "Inspiratory 'whoop' on cough is the pathognomonic sign", "Three clinical stages: (1) catarrhal — cold-like symptoms; (2) paroxysmal — severe coughing fits with whoop; (3) convalescent — gradual resolution", "DTaP vaccine (acellular pertussis component: filamentous hemagglutinin + pertussis toxoid); immunity wanes after 5-7 years, requiring boosters"], "reservoir": "Humans", "transmission": "Respiratory droplets", "detailedPathogenesis": "Stage 1 (catarrhal, ~1-2 weeks): nasal congestion, rhinorrhea, sneezing resembling a common cold. Stage 2 (paroxysmal): severe coughing fits, 10-20 consecutive coughs, followed by a forceful inspiratory effort producing the characteristic 'whoop' sound; patient appears exhausted and short of breath. Stage 3 (convalescent): coughing gradually decreases over about 2 weeks, though can persist for months in some patients; rare cases develop encephalitis.", "additionalNotes": "Vaccination with inactivated whole-cell or acellular vaccine, combined with diphtheria and tetanus toxoids (DTaP), is the mainstay of prevention."}, {"id": "l_pneumophila", "scientificName": "Legionella pneumophila", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Aerobic > Fastidious", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative (stains poorly with standard Gram stain)", "morphology": "Pleomorphic — round to rod-shaped to long filaments", "arrangement": "Variable", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic; fastidious, facultative intracellular", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Stains poorly with standard Gram stain despite being gram-negative", "Requires special media with increased iron and cysteine (BCYE — buffered charcoal yeast extract) for culture", "Tolerates high temperatures, persisting for months to years in environmental water sources"], "virulenceFactors": ["Facultative intracellular survival within host cells (notably amoebae in the environment and macrophages in humans)"], "diseases": ["Legionnaires' disease — severe atypical pneumonia, rapidly progressive, mortality ~10-20%", "Pontiac fever — milder, self-limited flu-like illness without pneumonia and without fatalities"], "labDiagnosis": ["Culture on BCYE agar (special media required)", "Urinary antigen test", "Clinical diagnosis supported by exposure history"], "examPearls": ["Classic exposure: elderly smoker, heavy drinker, or immunosuppressed patient with water aerosol exposure (air conditioning systems, cooling towers, showers)", "Found in moist environmental niches: faucets, refrigerators, air conditioner filters/cooling systems", "Legionnaires' (pneumonia, severe, ~10-20% mortality) vs Pontiac fever (no pneumonia, no deaths) — same organism, different severity", "Incubation: 2-10 days for pneumonia form, only 5-6 hours for Pontiac fever"], "reservoir": "Environmental water sources — plumbing, air conditioning systems, cooling towers", "transmission": "Inhalation of contaminated water aerosols", "predisposingFactors": ["Smoking", "Heavy alcohol use", "Immunosuppression", "Elderly age"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Inhaled in aerosolized water droplets; survives and replicates within alveolar macrophages (facultative intracellular). High fever (up to 41°C), cough, diarrhea, and abdominal pain are characteristic. The pneumonia form (Legionnaires' disease) progresses rapidly and severely; the non-pneumonic form (Pontiac fever) is self-limited.", "additionalNotes": "Prevention is difficult given environmental ubiquity; chlorination of water supplies is believed to help reduce organism load."}, {"id": "f_tularensis", "scientificName": "Francisella tularensis", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Aerobic > Small rod, zoonotic", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Small rod", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic; facultative intracellular", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Small gram-negative rod; fastidious growth"], "virulenceFactors": ["Facultative intracellular survival in reticuloendothelial cells"], "diseases": ["Ulceroglandular disease", "Atypical pneumonia", "Gastrointestinal disease"], "labDiagnosis": ["Serology; culture requires special precautions due to high infectivity"], "examPearls": ["Potential biowarfare agent — highly infectious", "Classic exposure: hunters in contact with rabbits, deer, ticks", "Zoonotic — wild animals, especially rabbits, deer, and rodents, are reservoirs", "Localizes in reticuloendothelial cells as a facultative intracellular pathogen"], "reservoir": "Wild animals — rabbits, deer, rodents", "transmission": "Direct contact with infected animals, tick bites, or inhalation", "predisposingFactors": ["Hunting/outdoor exposure to wild animals and ticks"]}, {"id": "h_influenzae", "scientificName": "Haemophilus influenzae", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Coccobacilli > Requires Factors X and V", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Small rod/coccobacillus", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe; fastidious", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Requires both Factor X (hemin) and Factor V (NAD) for growth — classic identifying requirement", "Polysaccharide capsule; type b capsule (polyribitol phosphate) is the most clinically important serotype", "Six serotypes overall: a, b, c, d, e, f"], "virulenceFactors": ["Polysaccharide capsule (type b, polyribitol phosphate) — most important virulence factor; basis for antigen detection (latex particle agglutination on CSF) and for Hib vaccine", "IgA protease — mucosal colonizing factor, degrades secretory IgA allowing mucosal adherence"], "diseases": ["Meningitis, pneumonia, epiglottitis — classically in unvaccinated children age 3 months to 2 years", "Bronchitis and pneumonia — in smokers with COPD"], "labDiagnosis": ["Requires Factor X and V for growth (chocolate agar or specific supplemented media)", "Latex particle agglutination for capsular antigen in CSF"], "examPearls": ["Factor X and V requirement is THE classic identifying lab feature for this organism", "Type b capsule = most important virulence factor and vaccine target (Hib vaccine)", "Classic patient profiles: unvaccinated young child (meningitis/epiglottitis) OR smoker with COPD (bronchitis/pneumonia) — two very different but both high-yield presentations"], "reservoir": "Human nasopharynx", "transmission": "Respiratory droplets", "predisposingFactors": ["Lack of Hib vaccination (young children)", "COPD/smoking (adults)"], "additionalNotes": "Six capsular serotypes overall (a-f); type b historically caused the most severe invasive disease before widespread vaccination."}, {"id": "h_parainfluenzae", "scientificName": "Haemophilus parainfluenzae", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Coccobacilli > Normal oropharyngeal flora", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Small rod", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Normal flora of throat and upper respiratory tract"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively characterized in source material"], "diseases": ["Endocarditis — particularly in patients with pre-existing rheumatic heart disease"], "labDiagnosis": ["Identified from blood culture in endocarditis workup"], "examPearls": ["Enters bloodstream through oral mucosal breaks — dental trauma, gum disease, or dental procedures", "Important reminder that normal flora organisms can cause endocarditis given the right host risk factors (damaged valve + transient bacteremia)"], "reservoir": "Normal flora of human throat and upper respiratory tract", "transmission": "Endogenous — enters bloodstream via oral mucosal trauma (gum disease, dental work)", "predisposingFactors": ["Pre-existing rheumatic heart disease", "Dental disease/procedures"]}, {"id": "h_ducreyi", "scientificName": "Haemophilus ducreyi", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Coccobacilli > Sexually transmitted", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Small rod", "arrangement": "Single/chains", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe; fastidious", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Fastidious organism associated with genital ulcer disease"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively characterized in source material"], "diseases": ["Chancroid (soft chancre) — painful genital ulcer with soft, irregular borders; can progress to painful inguinal lymphadenopathy (bubo)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis based on ulcer characteristics; culture is difficult"], "examPearls": ["SOFT chancre = H. ducreyi (painful, irregular border) — contrast with HARD chancre of syphilis (painless, indurated)", "Inguinal lymphadenopathy/bubo formation is a classic complication"], "reservoir": "Human genitals", "transmission": "Sexual contact and direct contact", "detailedPathogenesis": "Enters through skin breaks/abrasions, especially genital skin, producing a raised red lesion within 2-14 days that develops into a painful, soft, ragged-edged ulcer (distinguishing it from the painless, indurated 'hard chancre' of syphilis). Infection can spread to inguinal lymph nodes, causing painful swollen nodes (bubo)."}, {"id": "p_multocida", "scientificName": "Pasteurella multocida", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Coccobacilli > Animal-bite associated", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Small rods", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Bipolar staining", "Small gram-negative rods"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively characterized in source material"], "diseases": ["Cellulitis/lymphadenitis following animal bite/scratch", "Can spread to joints, bone, and lymph nodes in weakened hosts; bloodstream spread to vital organs (heart, CNS) possible"], "labDiagnosis": ["Bipolar-staining gram-negative rod cultured from bite wound"], "examPearls": ["Classic exposure: cat or dog bite/scratch", "Found in mouths of many animals, especially cats and dogs"], "reservoir": "Mouths of many animals, especially cats and dogs", "transmission": "Animal bite or scratch", "additionalNotes": "Disease can progress from local cellulitis to involve joints, bones, lymph nodes; in weakened patients, can become systemic affecting heart and CNS."}, {"id": "e_coli", "scientificName": "Escherichia coli", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Lactose fermenter (Coliform) > Oxidase (−)", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Oxidase negative", "Lactose fermenter — colonies with methylene/methilic green sheen on EMB agar", "Most abundant facultative organism in human/animal colon", "Cannot survive long outside the body (1-2 weeks) — unlike Klebsiella/Enterobacter which can free-live"], "virulenceFactors": ["Colonizing Factor Antigen (CFA) — adherence to intestinal wall (ETEC)", "Heat-labile enterotoxin (LT) — destroyed at 60°C/30min; large protein, antigenic; mechanism similar to cholera toxin", "Heat-stable enterotoxin (ST) — survives 100°C/30min; small protein, non-antigenic; STa activates guanylate cyclase, raising cGMP and causing fluid/electrolyte secretion", "Verocytotoxin (Shiga-like toxin) — heat-labile, cytotoxic to Vero cells, damages vascular endothelium; similar to S. dysenteriae type 1 shiga toxin", "K antigen — enables invasion in EIEC strains"], "diseases": ["Urinary tract infection — most common cause (~90% of acute uncomplicated UTI), especially in women due to short, straight urethra", "Wound/surgical/burn infections", "Biliary tract infection (cholangitis, cholecystitis)", "Liver abscess", "Intra-abdominal infections (often polymicrobial) — peritonitis, appendiceal/perinephric/subdiaphragmatic abscess", "Endometritis", "Aspiration pneumonia (post-surgical or with septicemia)", "Neonatal meningitis", "Sepsis", "Diarrheal disease (specific pathogenic strains — EPEC, ETEC, EIEC, EHEC/VTEC)", "Hemolytic Uremic Syndrome (HUS) — complication of enterohemorrhagic strains, especially O157:H7"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative rod, oxidase negative", "Lactose fermenter — methylene green sheen on EMB agar", "Pathogenic diarrhea-causing strains cannot be distinguished biochemically from normal-flora E. coli; require serotyping or specialized assays (research-level animal assays historically used)"], "examPearls": ["EPEC — infants/young children, no clear toxin mechanism understood (historical classification)", "ETEC — classic traveler's diarrhea; needs BOTH CFA (to adhere) and enterotoxin (LT and/or ST) to cause disease", "EIEC — non-motile, non-lactose fermenting, dysentery-like via M-cell invasion and actin-based intracellular motility (mirrors Shigella mechanism)", "EHEC/VTEC — O157:H7 is the classic serotype; verocytotoxin causes hemorrhagic colitis and HUS (anemia from RBC destruction, renal failure, can be fatal)", "Most common cause of nosocomial gram-negative bacteremia and UTI overall"], "reservoir": "Normal colon flora of humans and animals (permanent resident); also found in external genitalia, vagina in smaller numbers", "transmission": "Endogenous spread (UTI, wound infection); fecal-oral for diarrheagenic strains (contaminated food/water)", "predisposingFactors": ["Female anatomy (short, straight urethra) for UTI", "Surgery for wound/biliary/intra-abdominal infections", "Travel to endemic areas for ETEC"], "detailedPathogenesis": "As normal colonic flora, E. coli causes opportunistic infection wherever it gains access to normally sterile sites (urinary tract via ascending colonization, peritoneum via bowel perforation/surgery, bloodstream via any breach). Diarrheagenic mechanisms vary by pathotype: ETEC adheres via CFA and secretes enterotoxins causing secretory (non-inflammatory) diarrhea; EIEC invades intestinal M cells and epithelium (membrane ruffling, macropinocytosis) causing dysentery; EHEC/VTEC strains produce Shiga-like verocytotoxin that damages vascular endothelium, causing hemorrhagic colitis, with the toxin's systemic absorption in a minority of patients (especially children) triggering Hemolytic Uremic Syndrome — hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia, and acute kidney injury.", "additionalNotes": "Detection of E. coli in water/food/environmental samples is used as an indicator of fecal contamination and potential presence of other enteric pathogens (Salmonella, Shigella, Vibrio cholerae, Hepatitis virus)."}, {"id": "k_pneumoniae", "scientificName": "Klebsiella pneumoniae", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Lactose fermenter (Coliform) > Large capsule", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod with large polysaccharide capsule", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Large polysaccharide capsule", "Mucoid, lactose-fermenting colonies on MacConkey agar", "Can survive free-living in the environment (unlike E. coli)"], "virulenceFactors": ["Large polysaccharide capsule — antiphagocytic; some strains produce additional toxins"], "diseases": ["Pneumonia — classically in elderly patients with chronic lung disease, alcoholism, or diabetes; 'currant-jelly' sputum", "UTI — especially catheter-associated", "Septicemia — immunocompromised or nosocomial setting", "Meningitis (per Thai source notes)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Mucoid, lactose-fermenting colonies on MacConkey agar"], "examPearls": ["'Currant-jelly sputum' is the classic exam buzzword for Klebsiella pneumonia", "Classic patient: elderly, chronic lung disease, alcoholic, or diabetic", "Large capsule is the key virulence factor — visible as mucoid colonies", "Notable nosocomial pathogen with increasing antibiotic resistance"], "reservoir": "Normal intestinal flora of humans and animals; also free-living in soil/environment", "transmission": "Endogenous spread; nosocomial transmission", "predisposingFactors": ["Chronic lung disease", "Alcoholism", "Diabetes", "Urinary catheterization", "Immunosuppression"]}, {"id": "enterobacter", "scientificName": "Enterobacter spp.", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Lactose fermenter (Coliform)", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Lactose fermenter", "Can survive free-living in environment"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively characterized in source material"], "diseases": ["Urinary tract infection"], "labDiagnosis": ["Isolated from surgical wounds, CSF, sputum, and blood in addition to urine"], "examPearls": ["Found in soil, garbage, dairy products in addition to GI tract — broader environmental presence than E. coli"], "reservoir": "Soil, refuse, dairy products, intestinal tract", "transmission": "Endogenous and environmental exposure"}, {"id": "proteus", "scientificName": "Proteus mirabilis / Proteus vulgaris", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Non-lactose fermenter > Urease (+), swarming motility", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Swarming motility on agar (characteristic spreading growth pattern)", "Non-lactose fermenting", "Urease positive"], "virulenceFactors": ["Urease — hydrolyzes urea to ammonia and CO2, alkalinizing urine"], "diseases": ["UTI (often chronic/recurrent)", "Staghorn renal calculi (struvite stones)", "Wound infection, pneumonia, septicemia (opportunistic)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Swarming motility on agar plates", "Urease positive", "Non-lactose fermenting"], "examPearls": ["Urease → alkaline urine → precipitation of calcium and magnesium phosphate → STAGHORN (struvite) calculi — classic high-yield association", "Stones cause obstruction → urinary stasis → promotes further infection (vicious cycle)", "Alkaline pH also directly damages renal epithelial cells, worsening infection", "Related genera Morganella and Providencia behave similarly"], "reservoir": "Soil, animal feces, sewage/wastewater", "transmission": "Opportunistic — typically endogenous or environmental exposure in compromised hosts", "detailedPathogenesis": "Urease activity converts urinary urea into ammonia and CO2, raising urine pH to alkaline levels. This promotes precipitation of calcium and magnesium ammonium phosphate (struvite), forming staghorn calculi that obstruct urine flow, cause stasis, and perpetuate infection. The alkaline environment also directly damages renal tubular epithelial cells, worsening tissue injury and infection severity."}, {"id": "salmonella_typhi", "scientificName": "Salmonella enterica subsp. Typhi", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Non-lactose fermenter > H2S (+), encapsulated", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod, encapsulated", "arrangement": "Single, motile (peritrichous flagella)", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Encapsulated", "Non-lactose fermenter", "Produces H2S gas", "Motile"], "virulenceFactors": ["Capsule — aids survival inside macrophages by resisting phagosome-lysosome fusion", "Endotoxin"], "diseases": ["Typhoid fever — fever, abdominal pain; can progress to intestinal perforation or abscess in liver/urinary tract in severe cases"], "labDiagnosis": ["Widal test (serologic agglutination test)", "Non-lactose fermenting, H2S-producing colonies on enteric media", "Blood culture early in disease, stool culture later"], "examPearls": ["Survives and replicates INSIDE macrophages — resistant to macrophage killing due to decreased lysosome-phagosome fusion (key intracellular survival mechanism)", "Classic exposure: travel to an endemic area, fecal-oral transmission from human carriers (often via gallbladder carriage)", "Two vaccine types available: injectable (killed) and oral (live attenuated)", "Disease course: week 1 = high fever/headache; weeks 2-3 = diarrhea develops as fever declines; severe cases may perforate intestine"], "reservoir": "Humans only (no animal reservoir) — chronic carriers often harbor the organism in the gallbladder", "transmission": "Fecal-oral route from human carriers; contaminated food/water", "detailedPathogenesis": "Ingested bacteria survive gastric acid and reach the small intestine, where they invade and are taken up by macrophages. Unlike most bacteria, S. Typhi survives and multiplies within macrophages due to decreased phagosome-lysosome fusion, allowing systemic spread via the reticuloendothelial system. Endotoxin release contributes to fever and systemic symptoms. As the disease progresses (week 2-3), intestinal involvement causes diarrhea; severe cases can develop intestinal ulceration leading to perforation, or seed distant abscesses (liver, urinary tract).", "additionalNotes": "Incubation period approximately 2 weeks. Control measures: treat patients and carriers, promote good personal hygiene, sanitary disposal of feces, eat freshly cooked food."}, {"id": "salmonella_nontyphi", "scientificName": "Salmonella enterica, non-Typhi serotypes (S. enteritidis, S. typhimurium, S. choleraesuis)", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Non-lactose fermenter > H2S (+), motile", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod", "arrangement": "Single, motile", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe; grows with or without oxygen", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Non-lactose fermenter", "Motile, produces H2S", "Thousands of serotypes exist (S. enteritidis alone has ~17,000 sub-serotypes by antigen typing per source material)"], "virulenceFactors": ["Endotoxin"], "diseases": ["Enterocolitis — inflammatory diarrhea, follows ingestion of poultry products or handling pet reptiles", "Septicemia — very young or elderly patients", "Osteomyelitis — particularly in sickle cell disease patients", "S. choleraesuis — zoonosis of swine origin"], "labDiagnosis": ["Non-lactose fermenting, motile, H2S-producing colonies on enteric isolation media"], "examPearls": ["Classic exposure: poultry products, reptile pets (turtles, lizards, snakes)", "Osteomyelitis association with sickle cell disease is a classic board-exam pairing", "Distinguish from S. Typhi: non-Typhi serotypes are zoonotic (animal reservoirs) vs. S. Typhi which is human-only"], "reservoir": "Wide range of animals — poultry, reptiles, livestock (varies by serotype)", "transmission": "Ingestion of contaminated poultry/eggs; handling reptiles; zoonotic exposure"}, {"id": "shigella", "scientificName": "Shigella spp. (S. sonnei, S. flexneri, S. dysenteriae, S. boydii)", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Non-lactose fermenter > H2S (−), non-motile", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod", "arrangement": "Single, non-motile", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Non-motile", "Non-lactose fermenter", "Does not produce H2S"], "virulenceFactors": ["Endotoxin — causes fever", "Enterotoxin — destroys colonic mucosal cells, causing ulceration and bleeding", "Invasion via membrane ruffling/macropinocytosis into M cells, with actin-based intracellular motility allowing lateral cell-to-cell spread without re-entering the extracellular space"], "diseases": ["Shigellosis (bacillary dysentery) — acute bloody diarrhea with fever; S. dysenteriae causes the most severe disease"], "labDiagnosis": ["Non-motile, non-lactose fermenting, H2S-negative gram-negative rod"], "examPearls": ["Non-motile + non-lactose + H2S-negative = classic three-way differentiation from Salmonella", "Invades via M cells, then spreads laterally using actin polymerization ('actin jet trails') WITHOUT returning to the extracellular space — an elegant immune-evasion mechanism producing shallow ulcers (rarely invades blood vessels)", "S. dysenteriae produces Shiga toxin and causes the most severe disease among the four species", "Classic presentation: bloody, mucoid diarrhea with abdominal cramping/tenesmus (painful straining)"], "reservoir": "Human and primate large intestine", "transmission": "Fecal-oral via contaminated food and water", "detailedPathogenesis": "Ingested organisms reach the large intestine and invade M cells via membrane ruffling and macropinocytosis, entering the underlying cytoplasm. They replicate intracellularly and use actin polymerization to form 'actin jet trails' that propel them laterally into adjacent epithelial cells without returning to the extracellular environment — this produces shallow mucosal ulcers and largely avoids triggering systemic/bloodstream invasion. Endotoxin causes fever; enterotoxin further damages mucosal cells, causing inflammation, ulceration, and bloody/mucoid stools.", "additionalNotes": "Incubation period 1-4 days. Prevention: personal hygiene and sanitation control."}, {"id": "y_pestis", "scientificName": "Yersinia pestis", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Non-enteric", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Not found in the intestine, unlike most Enterobacteriaceae — classified separately as a non-enteric pathogen of this family"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed in source beyond clinical disease pattern"], "diseases": ["Bubonic plague — high fever, painful regional lymphadenitis (bubo), conjunctivitis; transmitted by flea bite from infected rodent", "Pneumonic plague — arises from septic pulmonary emboli in bubonic plague, or by inhalation from an infected individual; spreads via airborne transmission person-to-person"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis supported by exposure history and culture/serology"], "examPearls": ["Classic exposure: small rodents (rats) and their fleas", "Bubonic plague: flea bite → lymphatic spread → painful bubo (most often groin, also axilla)", "Pneumonic plague: airborne transmission, much more contagious and rapidly fatal than bubonic form", "Natural cycle: rodent reservoir hosts → flea vector → amplifying hosts (most mammals) → human exposure", "Historically devastating pandemic disease (the Black Death)"], "reservoir": "Wild rodents (natural endemic reservoir hosts)", "transmission": "Flea bite (bubonic); airborne respiratory droplets (pneumonic)", "detailedPathogenesis": "Bubonic form: flea bite introduces bacteria into skin, which travel via lymphatics to regional lymph nodes (most commonly groin, then axilla), causing intensely painful, swollen lymphadenitis (bubo). Pneumonic form arises either from hematogenous/septic spread to the lungs during bubonic plague, or from inhaling infectious respiratory droplets from another pneumonic plague patient — this form spreads efficiently person-to-person via airborne transmission and has historically caused major epidemics.", "additionalNotes": "Thailand reported its first plague case in 1904 in a Bangkok Indian merchant community (Thonburi side) and its last reported case in 1952 in Nakhon Sawan province, per the Thai source material."}, {"id": "y_enterocolitica", "scientificName": "Yersinia enterocolitica", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Non-lactose fermenter, non-H2S", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Non-lactose fermenter", "Does not produce H2S", "Found in intestines of various animals: pigs, goats, sheep, cattle, cats, dogs"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed beyond clinical pattern"], "diseases": ["Inflammatory diarrhea or pseudoappendicitis (mesenteric lymphadenitis mimicking appendicitis)", "Yersiniosis — acute enterocolitis with diarrhea, fever, headache"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative bacillus, non-lactose fermenter, non-H2S producer cultured from stool"], "examPearls": ["Classic exposure: cold climates, unpasteurized milk, pork", "Pseudoappendicitis presentation (mesenteric lymphadenitis mimicking appendicitis) is a key clinical pearl", "Incubation period 4-10 days"], "reservoir": "Pigs, goats, sheep, cattle, cats, dogs", "transmission": "Ingestion of contaminated food/water; zoonotic exposure"}, {"id": "y_pseudotuberculosis", "scientificName": "Yersinia pseudotuberculosis", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Facultative Anaerobic > Enterobacteriaceae > Non-lactose fermenter, non-H2S", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Similar to Y. enterocolitica but generally causes milder disease"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed in source material"], "diseases": ["Yersiniosis — milder than Y. enterocolitica; more often causes mesenteric lymphadenitis than direct intestinal mucosal disease"], "labDiagnosis": ["Culture from stool or lymph node tissue"], "examPearls": ["Tends to favor mesenteric lymph node involvement over intestinal mucosal disease, compared to Y. enterocolitica"], "reservoir": "Various animals (similar to Y. enterocolitica)", "transmission": "Ingestion of contaminated food/water; zoonotic exposure"}, {"id": "v_cholerae", "scientificName": "Vibrio cholerae", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Curved Rods > Oxidase (+), polar flagellum, alkaline media (TCBS)", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Curved rod (comma-shaped)", "arrangement": "Single, highly motile via single polar flagellum", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe; oxidase positive", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Oxidase positive", "Curved/comma-shaped rod with polar flagellum", "Grows on alkaline media but not acidic media (TCBS — thiosulfate citrate bile salt sucrose medium)", "Prefers alkaline conditions; dies rapidly in acidic environments"], "virulenceFactors": ["Cholera enterotoxin (choleragen) — ADP-ribosylates Gs-alpha protein, activating adenylate cyclase, raising cAMP, causing massive efflux of Cl- and water into the intestinal lumen"], "diseases": ["Cholera — severe non-inflammatory (secretory) diarrhea with massive fluid loss, 'rice water stools'"], "labDiagnosis": ["Curved gram-negative rod, oxidase positive, grows on TCBS agar (alkaline-tolerant, not acid-tolerant)"], "examPearls": ["Rice-water stools = pathognomonic description (mucus, epithelial cells, and huge numbers of organisms, classic 'starchy water' look and smell)", "Mechanism: cholera toxin permanently activates adenylate cyclase via Gs-alpha ADP-ribosylation → high cAMP → massive Cl-/water secretion", "Must ingest a large inoculum since gastric acid kills most organisms — high-protein foods can buffer stomach acid and facilitate infection", "Death within 10-18 hours possible from hypovolemic shock if untreated; mortality drops below 1% with adequate fluid/electrolyte replacement", "Oral rehydration solution (ORS) is first-line for mild-moderate cases; severe cases need IV fluids", "El Tor biotype has replaced classical biotype as the dominant circulating strain in Thailand since the 1960s (serotypes Inaba and Ogawa, plus O139 Bengal)"], "reservoir": "Found in natural fresh water; travel to endemic areas is a classic risk factor", "transmission": "Ingestion of contaminated food, water, or beverages; flies can mechanically transmit", "predisposingFactors": ["Poor sanitation/hygiene", "Crowded living conditions", "Low socioeconomic status"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Bacteria must survive transit through the acidic stomach (large inoculum or buffering high-protein food assists survival) to reach the alkaline small intestine, where they adhere and multiply without invading tissue. Cholera toxin's A subunit ADP-ribosylates the Gs-alpha subunit of adenylate cyclase, locking it in an active state; resulting elevated cAMP drives massive secretion of chloride and water into the intestinal lumen, producing the characteristic profuse watery 'rice water' diarrhea, leading to severe dehydration, electrolyte loss, and hypovolemic shock if untreated.", "additionalNotes": "In Thailand, outbreaks historically peak during the dry season (January-April), with year-round sporadic cases concentrated in coastal provinces (Samut Songkhram, Samut Sakhon, Samut Prakan, Chonburi). The disease is now officially termed 'severe diarrhea' in Thai public health reporting rather than 'cholera'.", "treatment": "Oral rehydration solution (ORS) for mild-moderate cases; IV fluids/electrolytes for severe cases or with vomiting. Antibiotics do not reduce diarrhea severity but shorten duration and amount of bacterial shedding, reducing transmission and carrier state."}, {"id": "v_parahaemolyticus", "scientificName": "Vibrio parahaemolyticus", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Curved Rods > Halophilic (NaCl-requiring), seafood-associated", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Curved rod, similar to V. cholerae", "arrangement": "Single, motile", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Grows well on media with 1-3% added NaCl (salt-tolerant/halophilic)"], "virulenceFactors": ["Enterotoxin (specific mechanism not detailed in source material)"], "diseases": ["Food poisoning — abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea (occasionally dysentery-like with bloody/mucoid stool)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative curved rod requiring salt-supplemented media for optimal growth"], "examPearls": ["Classic exposure: raw or undercooked seafood (fish, crab, shrimp, shellfish)", "Requires a relatively large inoculum to cause disease", "Generally low mortality, self-limited illness over 2-5 days", "Onset 2-48 hours after ingestion, variable based on inoculum size and individual gastric acidity"], "reservoir": "Marine/coastal waters and seafood", "transmission": "Ingestion of contaminated raw/undercooked seafood", "detailedPathogenesis": "Ingested with contaminated seafood; if sufficient inoculum survives gastric acid, organisms multiply rapidly in the small intestine and produce enterotoxin, causing the classic food-poisoning symptom complex of abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea."}, {"id": "c_jejuni", "scientificName": "Campylobacter jejuni", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Curved Rods > Oxidase (+), microaerophilic, grows at 42°C, gull-wing", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Curved rod, both ends pointed", "arrangement": "Single, with polar flagella on one or both ends ('gull-wing' shape under microscopy)", "oxygenRequirement": "Microaerophilic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Oxidase positive", "Curved rod with polar flagella, gull-wing appearance", "Grows at 42°C (selective feature for isolation)"], "virulenceFactors": ["CJT toxin — causes inflammatory diarrhea (per Thai source material)"], "diseases": ["Inflammatory diarrhea — fever, bloody stools from intestinal ulceration", "Complication: Guillain-Barré syndrome (post-infectious autoimmune neuropathy)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative curved rod, oxidase positive, microaerophilic, grows selectively at 42°C"], "examPearls": ["'Gull-wing' or 'seagull shape' on Gram stain is the classic visual descriptor", "Most common transmission source: poultry (also cattle, goats, sheep, rodents)", "Guillain-Barré syndrome is a well-known post-infectious complication — high-yield association", "Invades and damages colonic mucosa, causing blood and pus in stool (inflammatory diarrhea pattern, distinct from cholera's secretory pattern)"], "reservoir": "Various animals — cattle, goats, sheep, rodents, poultry (chickens especially)", "transmission": "Fecal-oral, primarily from poultry; contaminated food and water", "detailedPathogenesis": "Ingested organisms reach the small intestine, invade the mucosa, multiply, and produce toxin (CJT) causing inflammatory diarrhea resembling cholera in volume but with high fever and bloody stools due to mucosal ulceration. Most healthy patients recover within 5-8 days without treatment.", "additionalNotes": "Incubation period 1-10 days per Thai source material."}, {"id": "h_pylori", "scientificName": "Helicobacter pylori", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Curved Rods > Oxidase (+), urease (+), microaerophilic, helical", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Helical bacilli", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Microaerophilic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Oxidase positive", "Urease positive — produces ammonium cloud that neutralizes stomach acid locally", "Helical/spiral morphology"], "virulenceFactors": ["Urease — generates ammonia to buffer gastric acid locally, allowing survival in the stomach", "Mucinase — aids penetration of the protective mucous layer", "Vacuolating cytotoxin (produced by biotype I strains) — contributes to mucosal damage"], "diseases": ["Chronic gastritis", "Duodenal/gastric ulcers", "Associated with increased risk of gastric cancer"], "labDiagnosis": ["Urease testing (e.g., urea breath test)", "Biopsy with histology/culture", "Urease-positive, oxidase-positive, microaerophilic helical organism on culture"], "examPearls": ["Urease-positive is the defining and clinically exploited feature (basis of the urea breath test for diagnosis)", "Two biotypes exist (I and II); type I produces vacuolating cytotoxin and is associated with more severe disease", "Chronic infection is linked to several forms of gastric cancer — important long-term consequence"], "reservoir": "Human stomach (chronic colonization)", "transmission": "Likely fecal-oral or oral-oral; exact mechanism not detailed in source material", "detailedPathogenesis": "Survives the highly acidic gastric environment by producing urease, which hydrolyzes urea into ammonia, creating a local protective cloud that neutralizes stomach acid immediately around the bacterium. Mucinase helps the organism burrow through the protective gastric mucous layer to reach the underlying epithelium, where chronic colonization triggers persistent inflammation (gastritis) and can progress to ulceration. Type I strains producing vacuolating cytotoxin are associated with more severe mucosal damage and higher risk of malignant transformation over time."}, {"id": "b_fragilis", "scientificName": "Bacteroides fragilis", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Anaerobic > Bile-esculin (+)", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Rod, pleomorphic (variable shapes/sizes)", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Anaerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Predominant anaerobe of the human colon", "Bile-esculin positive growth pattern"], "virulenceFactors": ["Capsule (implied by abscess-forming capacity); specific toxins not detailed in source material"], "diseases": ["Septicemia", "Peritonitis — often mixed/polymicrobial infections", "Abdominal abscess"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative anaerobic rod isolated from abscess/peritoneal fluid", "Bile-esculin agar growth pattern"], "examPearls": ["Classic exposure: abdominal trauma, emergency abdominal surgery", "The genus Bacteroides is THE predominant anaerobe of the human colon — important baseline fact", "Infections are often polymicrobial (mixed with aerobic enteric organisms)"], "reservoir": "Human colon (predominant anaerobic flora); also found in urinary tract, lungs, pelvis", "transmission": "Endogenous — released into normally sterile spaces via trauma or surgery (bowel perforation)", "predisposingFactors": ["Abdominal trauma", "Emergency abdominal surgery"]}, {"id": "fusobacterium", "scientificName": "Fusobacterium spp.", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Rods > Anaerobic", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Variable shape, mostly rods with tapered, spindle-shaped ('fusiform') ends", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Anaerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Fusiform (spindle) shape with tapered ends", "Some species are normal flora of upper respiratory tract, GI tract, and reproductive system"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed in source material"], "diseases": ["Lung abscess", "Intra-abdominal abscess (similar disease pattern to Bacteroides)"], "labDiagnosis": ["Gram-negative anaerobic rod with characteristic fusiform/spindle shape"], "examPearls": ["Causes similar disease pattern to Bacteroides — important to know as a related anaerobic pathogen", "Normal flora in some body sites but can cause disease when normal barriers are breached"], "reservoir": "Normal flora of upper respiratory tract, GI tract, reproductive system (varies by species)", "transmission": "Endogenous spread when normal anatomical barriers are disrupted"}, {"id": "g_vaginalis", "scientificName": "Gardnerella vaginalis", "classificationPath": "Gram-Negative Coccobacilli > Pleomorphic, vaginal flora", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative (pleomorphic, variable staining)", "morphology": "Pleomorphic rods", "arrangement": "Variable", "oxygenRequirement": "Facultative anaerobe", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Clue cells (vaginal epithelial cells covered with adherent bacteria) seen on saline wet mount", "Positive whiff test