ndylomata lata; tertiary stage: gummas affecting CNS and cardiovascular system"], "labDiagnosis": ["Darkfield or fluorescent antibody microscopy of chancre/lesion fluid", "Specific serologic tests: FTA-ABS, TPHA", "Non-specific serologic tests: RPR, VDRL"], "examPearls": ["HARD chancre (painless, indurated) — contrast with H. ducreyi's SOFT chancre (painful)", "Three-stage disease course: primary (localized chancre) → secondary (disseminated, 'outbreak'/'ออกดอก' rash) → tertiary (years later, destructive gummas)", "Congenital syphilis possible via transplacental transmission", "Penicillin remains first-line treatment even after decades of use — minimal resistance development", "RPR/VDRL = non-specific screening; FTA-ABS/TPHA = specific confirmatory tests"], "reservoir": "Humans only", "transmission": "Sexual contact; direct contact with lesions; transplacental (mother to fetus)", "detailedPathogenesis": "Primary stage (10 days-3 months post-exposure): organism enters through mucous membrane breaks, producing a localized chancre (papule that ulcerates into a painless, indurated lesion) at the entry site. Secondary stage (3 weeks-6 months after primary chancre heals): hematogenous/lymphatic dissemination causes fever, headache, sore throat, generalized lymphadenopathy, and a diffuse maculopapular rash ('ออกดอก' — literally 'flowering out' in Thai). Tertiary stage (5-20 years later): the organism damages major organs — cardiovascular system (aortic aneurysm), CNS (neurosyphilis, psychiatric symptoms), and bone (gummatous destruction).", "additionalNotes": "Transmitted via three routes: sexual contact, contact with lesion exudate, and transplacental transmission to the fetus. Prevention: condom use, avoiding contact with secondary-stage lesions.", "treatment": "Penicillin (first-line, remains highly effective)."}, {"id": "t_pertenue", "scientificName": "Treponema pertenue", "classificationPath": "Spirochetes > Treponema", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative, spiral", "morphology": "Spiral/helical", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Microaerophilic/anaerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Closely related to T. pallidum but causes a distinct non-venereal disease"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed in source material"], "diseases": ["Yaws — chronic skin disease, non-venereal"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis; similar serologic cross-reactivity with syphilis tests"], "examPearls": ["Found in Thailand mainly in the southern region", "Transmitted by direct contact through pre-existing skin breaks (non-sexual)", "Children with poor hygiene are most commonly affected"], "reservoir": "Humans", "transmission": "Direct skin-to-skin contact through pre-existing wounds", "predisposingFactors": ["Poor hygiene", "Childhood (most affected demographic)"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Incubation period 3-4 weeks; initial inflammation and swelling at entry site, followed by ulcerating, weeping (but painless) lesions approximately 1-3 months later.", "additionalNotes": "Prevention: environmental sanitation improvement, proper wound cleaning and covering to prevent insect contamination."}, {"id": "t_carateum", "scientificName": "Treponema carateum", "classificationPath": "Spirochetes > Treponema", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative, spiral", "morphology": "Spiral/helical", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Microaerophilic/anaerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Causes a distinct chronic, non-fatal skin disease"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed in source material"], "diseases": ["Pinta — chronic skin disease with dry, scaly, variably pigmented lesions"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis"], "examPearls": ["Most common among Black populations in Central America", "Not life-threatening but causes chronic, painful disfigurement"], "reservoir": "Humans", "transmission": "Close contact among populations with poor health/hygiene conditions", "additionalNotes": "Disease is chronic and disfiguring but not fatal."}, {"id": "t_vincentii", "scientificName": "Treponema vincentii", "classificationPath": "Spirochetes > Treponema", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative, spiral", "morphology": "Spiral/helical", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Anaerobic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Found in the oral cavity, typically in combination with other organisms"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not detailed in source material; pathogenic in combination with other oral flora"], "diseases": ["Vincent's infection (acute necrotizing ulcerative gingivitis) — typically a polymicrobial oral infection"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis; found alongside other organisms in oral specimens"], "examPearls": ["Causes disease in combination with other normal oral bacteria, rather than alone — classic example of polymicrobial/synergistic oral infection"], "reservoir": "Human oral cavity", "transmission": "Endogenous overgrowth of normal oral flora"}, {"id": "b_burgdorferi", "scientificName": "Borrelia burgdorferi", "classificationPath": "Spirochetes > Borrelia", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Larger spirochete than Treponema/Leptospira", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Microaerophilic; difficult to culture", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Larger size relative to other spirochetes", "Difficult to culture in vitro"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed; pathogenesis driven significantly by host immune complex formation"], "diseases": ["Lyme disease — influenza-like symptoms, erythema migrans (target/bullseye rash), can later involve heart, joints, and CNS"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis based on erythema migrans and exposure history; serology for confirmation"], "examPearls": ["Transmitted by Ixodes (deer) tick — classic high-yield vector", "Erythema migrans (target/bullseye rash) is the hallmark early clinical sign", "Disease spreads from skin via bloodstream to heart, joints, and CNS over time", "Arthritis in Lyme disease is caused by immune complex deposition, not direct bacterial joint destruction"], "reservoir": "Wild rodents and deer (enzootic cycle); ticks serve as vector", "transmission": "Ixodes (deer) tick bite", "detailedPathogenesis": "Tick bite introduces the organism into the skin, where local multiplication produces the characteristic expanding erythema migrans lesion. The organism then disseminates hematogenously to other organs — heart (carditis, conduction abnormalities), joints (arthritis, caused by immune complex-mediated inflammation), and central nervous system (neuroborreliosis)."}, {"id": "b_recurrentis", "scientificName": "Borrelia recurrentis", "classificationPath": "Spirochetes > Borrelia", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Large spirochete with wide, loose spirals", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Microaerophilic", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Large size with wide-spaced spiral coils"], "virulenceFactors": ["Antigenic variation allows the organism to evade immune clearance, producing the characteristic relapsing fever pattern"], "diseases": ["Relapsing fever — recurring episodes of high fever, severe headache, and muscle pain"], "labDiagnosis": ["Clinical diagnosis based on relapsing fever pattern and exposure history; blood smear during febrile episodes may show spirochetes"], "examPearls": ["Transmitted by louse bite (body louse)", "Classic relapsing pattern: fever lasts 3-4 days, resolves for 4-10 days, then recurs — can repeat 3-10 times", "Antigenic variation is the mechanism behind the relapsing pattern — immune system clears one antigenic variant, organism switches surface antigens, evades clearance, causing relapse"], "reservoir": "Humans (louse-borne form); other Borrelia species cause tick-borne relapsing fever with rodent reservoirs (not detailed in this source)", "transmission": "Louse bite", "predisposingFactors": ["Poor hygiene/clothing sanitation allowing louse infestation"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Incubation 3-10 days. Initial febrile episode (high fever, severe headache, myalgia) lasts 3-4 days, resolves as the immune system controls the initial antigenic variant population, then recurs as the organism switches surface antigens (antigenic variation) to evade the existing immune response — this relapsing cycle can occur 3-10 times before full resolution.", "additionalNotes": "Prevention: avoid louse/tick bites, maintain personal hygiene and clean clothing."}, {"id": "leptospira", "scientificName": "Leptospira interrogans (incl. L. icterohemorrhagiae)", "classificationPath": "Spirochetes > Leptospira", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Thin, tightly coiled spiral; ends typically curved into a hook shape", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Aerobic; motile by rotation along the long axis", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Terminal hook-shaped ends", "Motile via rotation along its long axis"], "virulenceFactors": ["Not extensively detailed in source material"], "diseases": ["Leptospirosis — influenza-like illness with possible GI symptoms; can progress to meningitis in some cases"], "labDiagnosis": ["Serodiagnosis via agglutination test"], "examPearls": ["Classic exposure: occupational/recreational water exposure (farmers, those wading through floodwater)", "Reservoir hosts: dogs, cats, horses, cattle, pigs, rats — organism lives in the kidney and is shed in urine", "Two entry routes: skin breaks/abrasions (direct water contact) or mucous membranes (eyes, nose, mouth)", "In Thailand, peak season is rainy season into early winter, with highest incidence in the Northeast region", "Classic at-risk occupations: farmers (rice, field, orchard workers)"], "reservoir": "Domestic and farm animals (dogs, cats, horses, cattle, pigs) and rodents (rats); organism resides in the kidney and is excreted in urine", "transmission": "Contact with water contaminated by animal urine; enters via skin abrasions or mucous membranes (eyes, nose, mouth)", "predisposingFactors": ["Occupational exposure (farming)