k bite, enters the bloodstream, and invades vascular endothelial cells throughout the body, where it replicates intracellularly (its inability to synthesize NAD+/CoA forces reliance on host cell metabolites). Endothelial damage causes vasculitis, producing the characteristic spreading rash and underlying vascular injury responsible for systemic complications."}, {"id": "r_prowazekii", "scientificName": "Rickettsia prowazekii", "classificationPath": "Obligate Intracellular > Rickettsia > Vector: Human louse", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Coccobacilli", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Obligate intracellular; non-motile; cannot synthesize own NAD+/CoA", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Gram-negative coccobacillus, non-motile, obligate intracellular — same general features as R. rickettsii but different vector and disease group"], "virulenceFactors": ["Obligate intracellular replication causing vasculitis"], "diseases": ["Epidemic typhus — high fever, severe headache, rash; historically associated with war, famine, and crowding"], "labDiagnosis": ["Serology; requires cell culture for isolation (not grown on artificial media)"], "examPearls": ["Transmitted by HUMAN LOUSE — classic vector, spread via louse feces contaminating bite wounds or skin breaks", "Reservoir: humans (unlike most other Rickettsia, which have animal reservoirs)", "Member of the Typhus Group (vs. Spotted Fever Group for R. rickettsii)", "Classic historical association: crowded, unsanitary conditions (wartime, refugee camps, famine)"], "reservoir": "Humans", "transmission": "Human body louse (transmitted via louse feces, not direct bite — feces deposited on skin are scratched into the bite wound or abrasions)", "predisposingFactors": ["Crowding", "Poor sanitation", "War/famine conditions favoring louse infestation"], "detailedPathogenesis": "Louse feeds on infected human, acquires the organism, and sheds it in feces during subsequent feeding on a new host; the new host autoinoculates the organism by scratching louse feces into the bite site or skin breaks. The organism then disseminates and invades vascular endothelium, causing systemic vasculitis responsible for fever, rash, and potential severe complications."}, {"id": "r_typhi", "scientificName": "Rickettsia typhi", "classificationPath": "Obligate Intracellular > Rickettsia > Vector: Flea", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Coccobacilli", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Obligate intracellular; non-motile; cannot synthesize own NAD+/CoA", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Gram-negative coccobacillus, non-motile, obligate intracellular — same general profile as other Rickettsia species"], "virulenceFactors": ["Obligate intracellular replication causing vasculitis"], "diseases": ["Murine typhus (endemic typhus) — generally milder than epidemic typhus; fever, headache, rash"], "labDiagnosis": ["Serology; requires cell culture for isolation"], "examPearls": ["Transmitted by FLEA bite — classic vector (rat flea)", "Reservoir: rodents — hence 'murine' typhus", "Member of the Typhus Group, alongside R. prowazekii, but milder disease and zoonotic (rodent) rather than human reservoir", "'Endemic' typhus contrasts with 'epidemic' typhus (R. prowazekii), reflecting the steady rodent-flea cycle versus explosive louse-borne outbreaks"], "reservoir": "Rodents (rats)", "transmission": "Rat flea bite", "detailedPathogenesis": "Flea bite introduces the organism into the skin; it disseminates and invades vascular endothelial cells, causing vasculitis similar to other rickettsial infections but generally producing milder systemic disease than epidemic typhus."}, {"id": "orientia_tsutsugamushi", "scientificName": "Orientia tsutsugamushi", "classificationPath": "Obligate Intracellular > Rickettsia-related > Vector: Mite (chigger)", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Coccobacilli", "arrangement": "Single", "oxygenRequirement": "Obligate intracellular", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Closely related to Rickettsia genus; transmitted by a distinct vector (mite/chigger rather than tick, louse, or flea)"], "virulenceFactors": ["Obligate intracellular replication"], "diseases": ["Scrub typhus — fever, headache, eschar at bite site, rash, lymphadenopathy"], "labDiagnosis": ["Serology"], "examPearls": ["Transmitted by MITE (chigger) bite — distinct vector from the true Rickettsia species", "Reservoir: rodents", "Classic exposure: walking through scrub/grassy vegetation in endemic areas (notably parts of Asia, including Thailand)", "Eschar at the bite site is a classic clinical clue, similar in concept to the tick-bite eschar of some spotted fever group rickettsioses"], "reservoir": "Rodents", "transmission": "Mite (chigger) bite"}, {"id": "ehrlichia", "scientificName": "Ehrlichia chafeensis / Ehrlichia phagocytophila", "classificationPath": "Obligate Intracellular > Rickettsia-related > Vector: Tick", "gramReaction": "Gram-negative", "morphology": "Coccobacilli", "arrangement": "Single; characteristically forms intracellular clusters called morulae within white blood cells", "oxygenRequirement": "Obligate intracellular (infects leukocytes specifically, unlike Rickettsia which targets endothelial cells)", "distinguishingFeatures": ["Infects white blood cells (monocytes or granulocytes depending on species), forming visible intracellular inclusion clusters (morulae) on blood smear"], "virulenceFactors": ["Obligate intracellular survival within leukocytes"], "diseases": ["Ehrlichiosis — fever, headache, myalgia; can range from mild to severe"], "labDiagnosis": ["Blood smear may show morulae (clusters of organisms) within leukocytes", "Serology"], "examPearls": ["Transmitted by TICK bite", "Reservoir: small mammals", "Unlike Rickettsia (which infects vascular endothelium), Ehrlichia infects white blood cells — an important distinguishing pathogenic feature", "Grouped alongside the other tick/louse/flea/mite-borne organisms on the Rickettsia sum